{"title_page": "Judicial populism", "text_new": "'''Judicial populism''' or '''juridical populism''' is a phenomenon where the judgments and actions of the courts are driven by the masses' or certain groups' perception of justice.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=Li|first=Yuwen|title=The Judicial System and Reform in Post-Mao China: Stumbling Towards Justice|date=2016|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=978-1-317-02655-6|location=Oxon|pages=}}</ref> The term, which some refer to as \"popular constitutionalism\", has been described as a reaction to the perceived elitist bias in the legal system and can also refer to the actions of the courts that reflect public sentiment or garner public support for the judicial institution.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Hammergren|first=Linn|title=Envisioning Reform: Improving Judicial Performance in Latin America|date=2010|publisher=The Pennsylvania State University Press|year=|isbn=0-271-02933-1|location=University Park, PA|pages=93}}</ref> \n\n== Background ==\n[[File:Police Everywhere Justice Nowhere, rally at the State Capitol in St Paul, MN after the not guilty verdict in the Yanez trial (34543469773).jpg|left|thumb|260x260px|Judicial populism addresses the argument that the judicial institution does not represent the interest of the public or a group of people.]]\nJudicial populism is considered an aspect of [[Populism|populist politics]], particularly the strand that claims to represent the interests of the people against a corrupt elite.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/politics-populism-and-the-law-who-really-speaks-for-the-kenyan-people-83889|title=Politics, populism and the law: who really speaks for the Kenyan people?|last=Chengeta|first=Thompson|website=The Conversation|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> Due to accusations of excessive privileges, inefficiencies, and possible corruption, there is an increased hostility towards the judicial system and the creation of an atmosphere of distrust for the courts.<ref name=\":0\" /> Activism among populist groups calls for judicial decisions that reflect the collective will of the people. \n\nIn response, there are court judgments that are made as a form of self-representation to appease the public, obtain support or legitimacy by reflecting public sentiment. This can be demonstrated in the so-called dialectic court proceedings, which no longer focus on the evaluation of evidence but their legitimacy.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=Delledonne|first=Giacomo|title=Italian Populism and Constitutional Law: Strategies, Conflicts and Dilemmas|last2=Martinico|first2=Giuseppe|last3=Monti|first3=Matteo|last4=Pacini|first4=Fabio|date=2020|publisher=Springer Nature|year=|isbn=978-3-030-37400-6|location=Cham, Switzerland|pages=14, 306}}</ref> The position is that this type of populism can reduce the alienation or distance of citizens to the judicial institution due to an expectation that decisions are more meaningful to their lives.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThere are also theorists who maintain that judicial decisions are anti-democratic in character and view these decisions as judicial intervention.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Gargarella|first=Roberto|title=Courts and Social Transformation in New Democracies: An Institutional Voice for the Poor?|last2=Roux|first2=Theunis|date=2017|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=978-1-351-94795-4|location=Oxon|pages=}}</ref> This position is prominent in the antagonism towards decisions involving social rights where the constitutional backgrounds of judges are considered inadequate due to issues of technical competence or a perceived judicial prejudice.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn the United States, the call for judicial populism also emerges according to political ideologies. In the past, it came with the [[Conservatism|conservative]] assault to the so-called \"judicial supremacy\" as the courts outlawed [[Racial segregation|segregation]] and protected [[Reproductive rights|reproductive freedom]], among other issues.<ref name=\":4\" /> In the modern period, the call is often made by liberal critics who assail what is perceived as \"right-wing rulings\".<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|last=Tribe|first=Laurence H.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/10/24/books/review/the-people-themselves-judicial-populism.html|title='The People Themselves': Judicial Populism|date=2004-10-24|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-08|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n== Concept ==\nAs a theory, judicial populism holds that the law emanates from some kind of collective general will.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Schecter|first=Darrow|title=Critical Theory in the Twenty-First Century|date=2013|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing USA|year=|isbn=978-1-4411-0546-2|location=New York|pages=36}}</ref> It is founded on democratic and [[participatory theory]] wherein the people or at least their elected representatives get to decide policy, the state's developmental path, and the administration of justice.<ref name=\":1\" /> [[Larry Kramer (legal scholar)|Larry Kramer]], for instance, argued that the people do not only shared in construing the Constitution but also renders the final judgment concerning its meaning.<ref name=\":4\" /> The concept is also a basis of the Chinese legal tradition established during the [[Maoism|Maoist]]-era and its modern revival.<ref>Carl Minzner, ''Legal Reform in the Xi Jinping Era'', 20 Asia Policy. 4 (2015)</ref> It draws from the cultural belief of the non-finality of justice as well as the [[Communism|Communist]] revolutionary values such as democratic justice and [[Deliberative democracy|deliberative justice]], which rely on the collective judgment of the people.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nThe opposing concept to judicial populism is judicial professionalism. This view maintains that knowledge, rationality, and [[ethics]] should be the focus in legal practice.<ref name=\":2\" /> There is also a requirement for judges to be neutral and to avoid conflict of interest, which is present in judicial populism where the judge is involved in local affairs and forges a close relationship with the people.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite book|last=Alford|first=William P.|title=Prospects for the Professions in China|last2=Kirby|first2=William|last3=Winston|first3=Kenneth|date=2010-10-07|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=978-1-136-90992-4|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref> \n\n== Applications ==\nAn example of judicial populism is Mark Tushnet's suggestion of a populist American constitutional law that advances the so-called \"thin Constitution\", which would codify constitutionally protected and enforceable positive economic and social rights.<ref>{{Cite book|last=White|first=Charles S.|title=Democracy's Discontent and Civic Learning: Multiple Perspectives|date=2018-09-01|publisher=IAP|year=|isbn=978-1-64113-339-5|location=Charlotte, NC|pages=138}}</ref> \n\nThere is also the case of judicial elections, which has been identified as an instrument of popular constitutionalism.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pozen|first=David E.|date=2010|title=Judicial elections as popular constitutionalism|journal=Columbia Law Review|volume=110|issue=8|pages=2047\u20132134|issn=0010-1958|via=}}</ref> This framework emphasizes the importance of state judicial elections in the United States, particularly how the elected state justices can \"stimulate and structure constitutional deliberations\" on the national level.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mansker|first=Nicole|last2=Devins|first2=Neal|date=April 3, 2011|title=Do Judicial Elections Facilitate Popular Constitutionalism; Can they?|url=|journal=Columbia Law Review|volume=111|pages=27-37|via=}}</ref>\n\n[[Mass media]] has been cited for its role in dictating judicial agenda.<ref name=\":3\" /> It serves as a platform where the judicial institution is evaluated, facilitating new types of accountability regarding how justice is administered.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|last=Gandhi|first=Praveen Kumar|title=Social Action Through Law|date=1985|publisher=Concept Publishing Company|year=|isbn=|location=New Delhi|pages=64}}</ref> For instance, it is claimed that this development has led to juristic activism that favor a populist expansion of [[fundamental rights]] and [[natural justice]]. <ref name=\":5\" />  \n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n[[Category:Theories of law]]\n[[Category:Legal systems]]\n[[Category:Sociology of law]]\n[[Category:Legal history]]\n[[Category:Jurisprudence]]\n[[Category:Populism]]\n", "text_old": "'''Judicial populism''' or '''juridical populism''' is a phenomenon where the judgments and actions of the courts are driven by the masses' or certain groups' perception of justice.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=Li|first=Yuwen|title=The Judicial System and Reform in Post-Mao China: Stumbling Towards Justice|date=2016|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=978-1-317-02655-6|location=Oxon|pages=}}</ref> The term, which some refer to as \"popular constitutionalism\", has been described as a reaction to the perceived elitist bias in the legal system and can also refer to the actions of the courts to reflect public sentiment or garner public support for the judicial institution.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Hammergren|first=Linn|title=Envisioning Reform: Improving Judicial Performance in Latin America|date=2010|publisher=The Pennsylvania State University Press|year=|isbn=0-271-02933-1|location=University Park, PA|pages=93}}</ref> \n\n== Background ==\n[[File:Police Everywhere Justice Nowhere, rally at the State Capitol in St Paul, MN after the not guilty verdict in the Yanez trial (34543469773).jpg|left|thumb|260x260px|Judicial populism addresses the argument that the judicial institution does not represent the interest of the public or a group of people.]]\nJudicial populism is considered an aspect of [[Populism|populist